column13: Rosvall, M., Esquivel, A. V., Lancichinetti, A., West, J. D., & Lambiotte
column57:
The table didn't completely horizontally fit into the page layout. It could maybe be made less spacey or made scrollable in such a way that the complete page does not have to be scrolled from left to right
Sources in a table cell could maybe be separated a bit more, maybe through more spacing or through line breaks

column56:
1. Table did not fit the screen, so I was forced to scale down the page, which greatly disrupted its readability. Still, the whole table did not even fit. 

2. Hyperlinks to articles did not make the scroll-down on the page low enough for the relevant article to be at the top of the page, since the page was already completely scrolled down. 

3. There is very little space between the different references, making the text look like one huge chunk.
column57:
1. Possible solution: fix the first row and column so that they are always visible.

2. Possible solution: highlight the line with the linked article at the bottom of the page.

3. Possible solution: add spacing.

column13: Rosvall, M., Esquivel, A. V., Lancichinetti, A., West, J. D., & Lambiotte, R
column57:
-A lot of dois are broken in the references due to some formatting issus (for example \textunderscore instead of an actuall _ in https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-030-05411-3\textunderscore 28 )

-It would be nice, if the dois are embedded and clickable links instead of plaintext.

-A pragraph mark after every entry would make the table much more readable.

-Tables with a lot of rows always have the problem the you can't see the column captions anymore after scrolling down to far. That makes them sometimes a bit cumbersome to use.  A nice way around this is to make the column captions detachable from the table, so they automatically stay on top of the screen.

Better presentation of the bibliography list

* Hyperlinks for urls
Other suggestions:
* Preview the source (author(s), year, title, ...) in the table when hovering the reference link
* Open the DOI url in an iframe so that the page does not have to be left.

Search and filter the table/references (by name, year, ...)

column56: I could not find the month and day of publishing of the papers, thus, I was unable to correctly sort the papers in the third task. Also, I would have wished for names of the columns to follow when i scroll (as a fixed header), so that I always know what column to look at.
column57: As said before, the top row of the table moves out of view when scrolling down. I would be nice if it would stay fixed at the top of the screen. Also, an improved and more polished look would help the table to look less as if just someone made him/herself a table for private use. I don't knwo how to express this better, but the table still looks very premature (of course this is just an "apha" version, just as a note for future improvements :) ).

nice idea, but more better usability would be nice. 
visualization type table might me good for comparisons but for finding entries it is maybe not the best choice.

column56: During the sorting of the random walk algos, some papers coming up multiple times proved to be a bit annoying. A small screen is definitely a drawback when searching in such a table.
column57: Maybe adding the exact date to the table or at least the references would be better, as having to search for the exact date myself proved to be cumbersome.
column58: Overall, ok to use as still pretty intuitive, but could definitely be done better.

column56:
Having to scroll down without seeing the coloumn categories was very cumbersome.
The overview after clicking the link was not very nice to use as simple scrolling could make you search very long for the desired paper.
column57:
When scrolling down, it would be better if the coloumn categories would fix to the top of the screen, such that they are always visible.
In the overview after clicking on a link, make spaces between the papers and possibly marked the paper that was clicked on in the table visualization.
